During my stay in Rome in 1887 Ι examined several of these late copies of Aetna, all of them more or less inter- polated. But it must be considered very unfortunate that the codex of the later fourteenth or early fifteenth century, which I discovered in the Corsini palace, and which contains a copy of the Culex¹ of unique importance, has preserved only the first six verses of Aetna, enough, however, to show that the archetype srorn which it was intended to be copied entire was good, and did not belong to the inferior class. Had we, I will not say the whole, but half of Aetna preserved to us in this codex, we might have been able to illumine some of the dark passages where C and S leave us groping.
